# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Default backtrack solution. If elements are similar we dont need to swap them because we will get the same permutation, so we use ``` ++pos; ``` in loop to find different from ```nums[i]``` number. After all we should use ```pos = i;``` for use correct pos in next itteration. 

# Complexity
- Time complexity: suggest
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: N! (if all numbers are unique there is N! factorial possible permutations)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    std::vector<std::vector<int>> permuteUnique(std::vector<int>& nums) {
        std::vector<std::vector<int>> output;
        std::vector<int> currSubset;

        std::sort(nums.begin(), nums.end());
        permutations(nums, 0, output);

        return output;
    }
private:
    void permutations(std::vector<int> const& nums, int pos, std::vector<std::vector<int>>& output) {
        output.push_back(nums);

        for(int i = pos; i < nums.size(); ++i) {
            auto tmp = nums;
            while (pos < nums.size()-1) {
                ++pos;
                if (tmp[i] != tmp[pos]) {
                    std::swap(tmp[i], tmp[pos]);
                    permutations(tmp, i+1, output);
                }
            }
            pos = i;
        }
    }
};
