solutions.content:
This problem is nice because it offers a few subtle challenges:
* we need to figure out how to get all the permutations; 
* we want to do so as efficiently as possible, without generating duplicates;
* partially connected with the previous one, we want to avoid unnecessary memory usage, so we should have our result variable already properly sized in advance.

Let's start with the last point, *shall we?* [imagine this bit pronounced with the tone of [the Critical Drinker](https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCSJPFQdZwrOutnmSFYtbstA)]

We know (or can google/derive) that the number of permutations we will get is equal to the factorial of the numbers of elements, divided by the factorial of the frequency of each of them.

So, for example, if our input is `{1,2,3,4,5}`, we will get `5!` permutations, that is to say `120`; if we were still given `5` elements, but they were, say, `{1,1,4,4,4}`, we will have  `5! / 2! / 3!` (since we have `2` `1`s and `3` `4`s), which is `10`.

And what about not generating duplicates? We can do it with the built-in `next_permutation` that will `return` us only the next different permutation, no matter whether we have duplicated elements or not. Even better if we try to replicate that behaviour ourselves, since it is good practice.

With that in mind, time to start, declaring externally a precomputed array `facts` with all the factorials up to `8` (our largest possible input); inside our function we will also declare:
* `len` as the size of our input;
* `resSize` as the size of our result, initially set to be the factorial of `len` (that we will also decrease, so that it will become the value of the last index of the input);
* `freqs` and `nFreqs` will store the frequencies of the positive and negative numbers we will be passed.

We will then loop through each element `n` in `nums` and:
* increased either `freqs[n]` or `nFreqs[-n]` by `1` (depending on whether or not `n` was positive);
* divide `resSize` by the updated frequence (which in turn will equate to dividing from the factorial of the overall frequence of each element).

Now that we have a proper value for `resSize`, we can create our last support variables `res` with the proper capacity, without consuming resources with several painful/expensive reallocations!

And now time to prepare `nums` - for convenience setting it to be our first permutation (ie:  the one with all its elements sorted in increasing order); I am fully aware this would not be strictly necessary, but since at some point we might reach a point in which we reach the last permutation (all the elements in decreasing order), and thus do the same, I just preferred to keep my logic a bit lighter and start with it.

We will write this value in `res[0]`.

Assuming `resSize > 1`, we will then loop `resSize` times, using also `j`, `k` and `n` as loop variables and for each iteration we will basically replicate the behaviour of `next_permutation` by:
* setting `j` to be the value of the rightmost element (`len`);
* looping `while` `j > 0` and:
	* checking when we have to create a new permutation, which is when we find that the the element right before `j` is actually smaller, in which case we will:
		* set `n` to be the preceding element (`nums[j - 1`);
		* set `k` to equal the initial value of `j`, that is to say the index of the rightmost element - `len`;
		* decrease `k` by `1` `while` nums[k] <= n`, to make it so that `k` is now pointing to the first element from the right greater than `n`;
		* swap `nums[j- 1]` and `nums[k]`;
		* if `j` is not still the last element `len`, we will then also sort `nums` from `j` onwards;
		* finally, we will `break` out of the loop, since we have now a valid permutation :)
	* increasing `j` by `1`
* writing the updated `nums` in `res[i]`.

For a more indepth analysis of the generation of the next permutation, I put some more words [in the solution of that specific problem](https://leetcode.com/problems/next-permutation/discuss/1044321/C%2B%2B-2-Pointer-Solution-Explained-100-Time-~90-Space) ok

Once done,  we can just `return` our efficiently computed `res` :)

The code:

```cpp
constexpr int facts[9] = {0, 1, 2, 6, 24, 120, 720, 5040, 40320};

class Solution {
public:
    vector<vector<int>> permuteUnique(vector<int> &nums) {
        // support variables
        int len = nums.size(), resSize = facts[len--], freqs[11] = {}, nFreqs[11] = {};
        // adjusting resSize
        for (int n: nums) {
            resSize /= ++(n > 0 ? freqs[n] : nFreqs[-n]);
        }
        vector<vector<int>> res(resSize);
        // preparing nums
        sort(begin(nums), end(nums));
        res[0] = nums;
        // adding all the other permutations to res
        for (int i = 1, j, k, n; i < resSize; i++) {
            // replicating next_permutation(begin(nums), end(nums));
            j = len;
            while (j) {
                // creating a new permutation, only when the next number is lower
                if (nums[j - 1] < nums[j]) {
                    // preparing the inner loop variables
                    n = nums[j - 1], k = len;
                    // looking for the first number > n, from right
                    while (nums[k] <= n) k--;
                    // swapping the number right before j and the one pointed by k
                    swap(nums[j - 1], nums[k]);
                    // sorting the rest
                    if (j != len) sort(begin(nums) + j, end(nums));
                    break;
                }
                j--;
            }
            res[i] = nums;
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```

