**Idea:**
We start the new sorted list with a zero node, so that it will be easier to insert in every position.
We iterate through the list with the `head` pointer.
For each node, we use the function `insert` to iterate through the new sorted list and find the right insertion position.
We return `new_head->next` because our zero node will always be first and we don't want it.

**Time Complexity:** O(n^2)
**Space Complexity:** O(1)
```
class Solution {
public:
    void insert(ListNode* head, ListNode* node) {
        while (head->next && head->next->val < node->val) head = head->next;
        node->next = head->next;
        head->next = node;
    }

    ListNode* insertionSortList(ListNode* head) {
        ListNode* new_head = new ListNode(0);

        while (head) {
            ListNode* node = head;
            head = head->next;
            insert(new_head, node);
        }

        return new_head->next;
    }
};
```
