solutions.content:
**Idea?**
* We need to sort the list using Insertion Sort.
* Insertion Sort works in **O(n^2) time**, each time picking up the new element and **inserting back this element** at the correct position in the sorted list found till now.

**Implementation 1:-(Not Efficient)**
* Each time when we pick up the new element, we need to **traverse in a backward manner** in the sorted list to insert this element at the correct position right?
* How do we traverse in a backward manner?
* We will be **reversing the sorted list up to the current node**.
* Then, we'll insert this new value at the correct position.
* Again **restore the original list by reversing again**.

```
class Solution {
public:
    // Time Complexity:- O(n^2)
    // Space Complexity:- O(1)
    // reverse the List upto the given node
    void reverseList(ListNode* head,ListNode* upto){
        ListNode *prev = NULL;
        while(head!=upto){
            ListNode* temp = head->next;
            head->next = prev;
            prev = head;
            head = temp;
        }
    }
    // insert the value at correct position
    void InsertValue(ListNode* curr){
        ListNode *nxt = curr->next;
        while(nxt!=nullptr and nxt->val>curr->val){
            swap(nxt->val,curr->val);
            nxt = nxt->next;
            curr = curr->next;
        }
    }
    ListNode* insertionSortList(ListNode* head) {
        ListNode* curr = head;
        while(curr!=nullptr){
            ListNode* temp = curr->next;
            reverseList(head,curr->next); // reverse the list prior to this node
            InsertValue(curr); // insert the value
            reverseList(curr,nullptr); // reverse the previous list again
            curr->next = temp;
            curr = curr->next;
        }
        return head;
    }
};
```

**Implementation 2:-(Efficient)**
* The above implementation is quite a hectic task, Can we improve it? **Can we insert a dummy node**?
* Okay, Let's make a dummy node.
* Each time when we encounter a new element, we'll find the correct position from the start of the sorted list(*starting from dummy node*) and find the position where this new value should be inserted.
* **Note:- Here we aren't reversing any list here.**

```
class Solution {
public:
    // Time Complexity:- O(n^2)
    // Space Complexity:- O(1)
    ListNode* insertionSortList(ListNode* head) {
        ListNode* dummy = new ListNode(-5005);
        ListNode* curr = head;
        while(curr!=nullptr){
            ListNode* nxt = curr->next; // store next node for iteration
            ListNode* iter = dummy;
            // iterate from the beginning and find the suitable position of curr->val
            while(iter->next!=nullptr and iter->next->val<curr->val)
                iter = iter->next;
            curr->next = iter->next;
            iter->next = curr; // insert node at this position
            curr = nxt;
        }
        return dummy->next;
    }
};
```
