solutions.content:
Lets take an example to understand what the code below does.

		4 -> 2 -> 1 -> 3

Also, as we know, in Insertion sort, we have a sorted sub-list to which we compare each element and then put it in its correct place. Initially, we assume that the first element is at correct place. We will do the same here.

So we first have a dummy node that will sit before the sorted sub-list because there may be cases when we want to put the node at first place in sorted list. 

			This is our sorted list in the beginning
			0 -> null

We start traversing our linked list. And because we want to compare each node value to every node in the sorted list, that means for each iteration, we need a pointer that start from the beginning of sorted list. That's why we do pointer = sorted inside the loop.

So our pointer always points to dummy node of sorted list in each iteration.

For first node i..e, node 4, since pointer.next is null, the node is simply attached to the sorted list. 

		  0 -> 4 -> null

For the second node i.e., node 2

We have another while loop which will compare each node value of sorted list with the current head node's value (until we reach the end of sorted list). If the value of a node in sorted list is less than value of head node, that means move ahead. Otherwise, if the value of a node in sorted list is greater than value of head node, that means we want to put our head node between pointer and pointer.next;

So, head node's value = 2.

pointer points to dummy node. So we start comparing pointer.next.val and head node's val

	  0 -> 4 -> null      head node's val = 2
         pointer          Since 4 > 2 the 2nd condition in while loop becomes false and we come out of loop.
	     .next

So, we put our node 1 between node 0 and node 4 i.e., between pointer and pointer.next.

Sorted list becomes - 

				0 -> 2 -> 4 -> null

Next we have node 1. Again, we start with pointer pointing to dummy node 0. Then our loop runs and we find that node 2's value > node 1'st value

So that means we have to place node 1 between node 0 and node 2. 

Sorted list becomes - 

				0 -> 1 -> 2 -> 4 -> null

Finally, we have node 3. The inner loop runs.
 pointer points to node 0
 is 1 < 3 ? YES. Move to next node. pointer points to node 1
 is 2 < 3 ? YES. Move to next node. pointer points to node 2
 is 4 < 3? NO! come out of the loop.

 So, we have to put node 3 between pointer and pointer.next. i..e, between node 2 and node 4

Sorted list becomes - 

				0 -> 1 -> 2 -> 3 -> 4 -> null

And our first loop ends as well since we reached the end of linked list. Hence, we return the sorted.next list (because we don't want to return dummy node).

```
public ListNode insertionSortList(ListNode head) {

        //If linked list has only one node
        if(head.next == null) return head;

        //The sorted linked list
        ListNode sorted = new ListNode(0);        
        while(head != null){

            ListNode pointer = sorted;
            /* 
            For the first node, pointer.next is null so this loop does not run and we simply attach
            first node to the sorted list, just how we do in insertion sort where we assume that first number 
            is already at correct place
            */
            while(pointer.next != null && pointer.next.val < head.val){
                pointer = pointer.next;
            }

            ListNode next = head.next;

            //Put the head node between pointer & pointer.next
            head.next = pointer.next;
            pointer.next = head;

            head = next;
        }


        return sorted.next;
    }
```

